#: ../../your-connections.rst:5
msgid "Your connections"
msgstr ""

#: ../../your-connections.rst:8
msgid "Knowing the right people won't get you a job, but it can help you."
msgstr ""

#: ../../your-connections.rst:9
msgid ""
"Does *who* you know matter as much as *what* you know? The answer is yes,"
" who you know can make a huge difference - but it might not be in the way"
" you think."
msgstr ""

#: ../../your-connections.rst:11
msgid ""
"Be clear that except in the most unusual and unlikely of circumstances, "
"**you are not going to land a job simply by knowing the right person**. "
"Nobody is going to \"get you a job\". The world just doesn't work like "
"that."
msgstr ""

#: ../../your-connections.rst:13
msgid ""
"What makes a difference is knowing people who know things, that they can "
"share with you: insights, knowledge, advice, perspectives experiences - "
"the things that this website tries to provide."
msgstr ""

#: ../../your-connections.rst:17
msgid "Networks of knowledge"
msgstr ""

#: ../../your-connections.rst:19
msgid ""
"As an African, you are most likely on the outside of the software "
"industry, looking in (and Africans who do make it into the industry, even"
" with great success, often say they feel that are still in some way "
"outsiders, looking in)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../your-connections.rst:21
msgid ""
"If you had been born say in San Francisco, perhaps you would have grown "
"up sitting at dinner tables with uncles and cousins talking about the "
"goings-on of Silicon Valley. It would be a familiar world, on your "
"doorstep. If you had studied at a European technical university, you "
"would have direct contact with people and conversations in the industry. "
"Living anywhere in the west, you would likely be within reach of plenty "
"of people familiar with jobs and job markets and the way these things "
"work."
msgstr ""

#: ../../your-connections.rst:23
msgid ""
"People in those situations benefit from having *networks of knowledge* "
"around them. There will always be someone who knows someone who has an "
"answer, or can give advice. No-one is going to get a job *just because* "
"they know someone, but there is real practical knowledge in those "
"networks of people - people who can say things like:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../your-connections.rst:25
msgid ""
"*You should apply to <xxx> - they have just advertised a job that fits "
"your profile perfectly.*"
msgstr ""

#: ../../your-connections.rst:26
msgid ""
"*At <yyy> they really care about your academic record - take it seriously"
" when you're asked about it.*"
msgstr ""

#: ../../your-connections.rst:27
msgid "*The problem with your CV is ...*"
msgstr ""

#: ../../your-connections.rst:28
msgid ""
"*You really ought to be considering developer relations or community "
"management roles.*"
msgstr ""

#: ../../your-connections.rst:29
msgid "*My goodness, whatever you do don't say that in your interview!*"
msgstr ""

#: ../../your-connections.rst:30
msgid ""
"*You're planning to say that your salary expectations are USD <nnn>?! You"
" must be joking! First, don't offer any information until you really need"
" to, and second, you can easily add another 50% to that figure.*"
msgstr ""

#: ../../your-connections.rst:32
msgid "And so on."
msgstr ""

#: ../../your-connections.rst:34
msgid ""
"If you're not surrounded by people able to say such things to you with "
"authority borne of experience, you're missing out on the gold dust that "
"some other people take so much for granted that they don't even know it's"
" gold dust."
msgstr ""

#: ../../your-connections.rst:38
msgid "Building your networks"
msgstr ""

#: ../../your-connections.rst:40
msgid ""
"You're going to have to build your own networks, and find ways to get "
"your own gold dust."
msgstr ""

#: ../../your-connections.rst:44
msgid ""
"\"Collecting people\" - as some seem to do on platforms such as LinkedIn "
"- is not building a network. A network must be formed of stronger "
"connections than that."
msgstr ""

#: ../../your-connections.rst:46
msgid ""
"In the absence of connections that simply come your way \"naturally\", "
"through your everyday social and work environment, you'll need to "
"cultivate them in other ways. *Cultivate* is the right word - they must "
"be nurtured and tended, consciously."
msgstr ""

#: ../../your-connections.rst:48
msgid ""
"That doesn't mean they can be *manufactured*. It's unsatisfying and "
"ineffective to approach them in a transactional way. If you approach any "
"relationship mainly from the perspective of your own advantage, it's not "
"going to create the kind of bond that you need."
msgstr ""

#: ../../your-connections.rst:52
msgid "Contribute your perspective"
msgstr ""

#: ../../your-connections.rst:54
msgid "Has knowing someone helped you? How?"
msgstr ""

#: ../../your-connections.rst:56
msgid ":ref:`How to contribute <contribute>`"
msgstr ""

#: ../../your-connections.rst:58
msgid ""
"Also, the value you get *out* of that kind of *network* is directly "
"related to the effort and value you put in. For example, it's cheap and "
"easy to form connections on social media, but they will be as cheap and "
"shallow as your own engagement in them."
msgstr ""

#: ../../your-connections.rst:62
msgid "Shared endeavour"
msgstr ""

#: ../../your-connections.rst:64
msgid ""
"Real connections will come most effectively from **shared endeavours** - "
"work that you do, things that you strive towards, efforts that you make, "
"together with others. An opportunity to work alongside others is a an "
"opportunity to develop the connections you need."
msgstr ""

#: ../../your-connections.rst:66
msgid ""
"In this at least, the playing field is levelled a bit more fairly. When "
"it's *possible* to do that work with others online, it matters less that "
"you're in a completely different part of the world. And if online is "
"where it takes place for *everyone*, the geographical advantage that "
"others might have enjoyed is less."
msgstr ""

#: ../../your-connections.rst:70
msgid "Do something you care about"
msgstr ""

#: ../../your-connections.rst:72
msgid ""
"It starts with something you genuinely care about. Whatever it is, you "
"can be pretty sure that it's something other people are interested in "
"too. It could be updating Open Street Map data for where you live, or "
"improving Wikipedia pages on topics you have expertise in, or programming"
" in Python, or something completely different."
msgstr ""

#: ../../your-connections.rst:74
msgid ""
"You will find that others also share that interest, and wherever there is"
" a shared human effort, personal relationships and social networks build "
"up around it. It can take a while for you to find them and even longer to"
" feel that you fit in, but those doors are there for participants. Your "
"caring and your participation in the effort are what will mean you "
"belong."
msgstr ""

#: ../../your-connections.rst:76
msgid "The connections will follow naturally."
msgstr ""

#: ../../your-connections.rst:80
msgid "Adjacent conversations"
msgstr ""

#: ../../your-connections.rst:82
msgid ""
"The subject-matter of the effort you participate in might not itself "
"touch the topics, related to work, careers and advancement, that you need"
" to help you. But there will *always* be adjacent conversations to any "
"effort people take part in together, and as you listen to and take part "
"in those, you will start to be exposed to the same networks of knowledge "
"and advice that can be so valuable."
msgstr ""

